04906nam a2200685Ia 9780801463099DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910338  a97808014630997 a10.7591/97808014630992doi  a(DE-B1597)478302  a(OCoLC)759160538  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aF127.H8bR64 2011 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a974.7/31 aRogers, Susan Fox, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMy Reach :bA Hudson River Memoir /cSusan Fox Rogers. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note to the Reader -- t1. What Lingers -- t2. My Reach -- t3. Swimming the Hudson -- t4. Courage -- t5. Home -- t6. A Life in a Boat -- t7. The Lost Dunes of Childhood -- t8. The Speed of Wind and Water -- t9. I’m Glad You Are Here -- t10. The Long Loneliness -- t11. Solace -- t12. Learning the River -- t13. If You Are Lucky -- t14. Fishing -- t15. Circling the City -- t16. Nubian Goats -- t17. Sturgeon Moon -- t18. Sitting by the River -- t19. Golden Club -- t20. Grave Sites -- t21. Summer Solstice -- t22. Love for a River -- tBooks Consulted -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this memoir of the Hudson River and of her family, Susan Fox Rogers writes from a fresh perspective: the seat of her kayak. Low in the water, she explores the bays and the larger estuary, riding the tides, marveling over sturgeons and eels, eagles and herons, and spotting the remains of the ice and cement industries. After years of dipping her paddle into the waters off the village of Tivoli, she came to know the rocks and tree limbs, currents and eddies, mansions and islands so well that she claimed that section of the river as her own: her reach. Woven into Rogers's intimate exploration of the river is the story of her life as a woman in the outdoors—rock climbing and hiking as well as kayaking. Rogers writes of the Hudson River with skill and vivacity. Her strong sense of place informs her engagement with a waterway that lured the early Dutch settlers, entranced nineteenth-century painters, and has been marked by decades of pollution. The river and the communities along its banks become partners in Rogers's life and vivid characters in her memoir. Her travels on the river range from short excursions to the Saugerties Lighthouse to a days-long journey from Tivoli to Tarrytown and a circumnavigation of Manhattan Island, while in memory she ventures as far as the Indiana Dunes and the French Pyrenees. In a fluid, engaging voice, My Reach mixes the genres of memoir, outdoor adventure, natural and unnatural history. Rogers's interest in the flora and fauna of the river is as keen as her insight into the people who live and travel along the waterway. She integrates moments of description and environmental context with her own process of grieving the recent deaths of both parents. The result is a book that not only moves the reader but also informs and entertains.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRiversxTravelzNew Jersey. 0aRiversxTravelzNew York (State). 0aRiverszNew JerseyxTravel. 0aRiverszNew York (State)xTravel. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aNature Guides & Natural History. 4aNew York History. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146309940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801463099/original  a9